The pork dumplings that I got weren't very spectacular either since it tasted a little bland with the chili oil not even able to save it. The mapo tofu though was REALLY spicy and I felt like it was a really good amount of spice as all mapo tofus should be. It was so good I felt myself sweating a bit while eating but the meat in the dish was really missing in the dish. While eating it, it didn't feel like there was any minced pork in there?  My friend, on the other hand,​ ordered a drink, happy Buddha, and we had to ask 4 different waiters before he actually got his drink. Keep in mind, the fourth waiter came up to us and asked if we were done with our dishes but he still didn't even get his drink yet. Overall not a bad food spot and the lunch menu was priced well considering we were in DeKalb​ food market hall.

Downtown Brooklyn has a lot of food options, including the 40 food vendors in Dekalb market. Despite all of those options, we frequently return to Han Dynasty, which serves great versions of classic Chinese dishes. Han Dynasty was founded by Han Chiang in Philadelphia, and many dishes reflect his Taiwanese and Sichuan heritage.  We get the eggplant in garlic sauce every time. Other favorites include wontons in chili oil, double cooked style (pork belly or chicken), fried rice, and Kung Pao chicken.  Service is also always friendly and energetic.

This restaurant gets 5 stars for the waiters and waitresses because they are kind , friendly and supportive . Our waitress explained the menu to us and suggested we share the plates because they were huge. We decided to take her advice and I was so glad we did because the portions of food were enough to fill us to the rim . We ordered Kung Pao Chicken , Chicken Fried Dumplings , Pork fried Rice, Fried Chicken Wings and the Happy Hour drinks which ended at 7:00.  The best part of our meal was the drinks and the Chicken Fried Dumplings. Oh my goodness those dumplings were the best dumplings I have ever had in my life . The chicken was completely cooked and well seasoned .  The Kung Pao Chicken was a bit chewy and full of peanut and peppers . The peanuts and peppers took away from the flavor of the chicken in my opinion but the food was still yummy .  My opinion of the fried rice is that it’s very unique . I feel this way because I’m use to standard fried rice which is a specific color and has a particular taste . This fried rice is not oily and lightly seasoned . The Pork is chewy and not dry like I am use to . It’s just.....one of a kind . I can’t describe the rice at all.  The Chicken wings are fried well and seem to be seasoned with pepper and salt after being cooked . The seasoning sits on top of the chicken skin rather than the flavor dissolving  into the meat like I prefer when meat is pre-seasoned .  However , the food was good and cheap . I may return .

Been here a couple of times, and enjoyed it. Unfortunately tonight a busy server literally got in a fight with the perfectly nice couple at the table next to us for no reason. It made the whole meal really tense and awkward.
I love this place. Spicy cucumbers are delish and the dan dan noodles are addicting. A little pricey but nothing out of the ordinary
The food is so good, fast service and friendly staff. It is best if you make a reservation in order to cut down on the wait time but overall great place.
I tried Han Dynasty for the first time in Brooklyn and the food was amazing. Everyone at my party loved the food and it was so delicious. The vegetable lo mein was my favorite.
Hottest🌟 🔥🌶 Chinese restaurant in BK/ the world! Great Art too! Try the Dan Dan noodles. They do not disap

Sat at the bar which had great service. The food came out SUPER fast and that threw us off a little.. was the food already sitting there ? And for how long? Anyways everything was warm and it tasted okay..
Wonderful service good staff love the food
Good wait staff, but rice dishes overcooked.

Tried the Dan Dan Noodles and one of the chicken lunch specials. Decent flavor. Way overcooked noodles. Not sure how to say this delicately, but the food made me and my dining partner very er...rumbly in the stomach and we had to urgently use the loo. Sorry to be graphic google, but you’ve been warned. Pass.

No complain and will visit here again. If you wanna find a spicy Chinese dishes, here is nice choose. The only thing I do not like is that too much oil in each plates which is not very healthy. Overall 4 star experience.
So good, try the dry pot and Dan Dan noodles. The scallion pancakes are amazing too.
Still the king of Dan Dan noodles.
The wontons in chili oil were the best I’ve had in years. Mike, the manager, generates wonderful hospitality AND made sure I got to my show upstairs on time.

Takeout food in the lunch menu was not properly cooked. Tofu in the lunch menu was terrible, some sauce spoiled the whole taste and made it uneatable. Dry Pepper chicken was over fried and the spices were messed up. Lunch menu is not recommendable especially takeouts.

So excited to have a legit delicious Chinese restaurant in the neighborhood! Everything we had was really good, wontons in chili oil, spicy braised beef and noodles in soup, double cooked chicken with rice, amazing! The fried chicken dumplings were ok, they were nice and crispy but were a bit lacking in flavor. Overall though, really great! Hope they deliver!!

10.20.17 - just as good if not better than the 3rd avenue location. We met two owners and their right hand man, who we first met three years ago at 3rd Avenue.  The only things we missed were the wings and the mungbean noodles. Overall, we're lucky to have this in the hood.

I love when a new restaurant that opens up in the neighborhood is actually good. Han dynasty has excellent tasting food and great service, especially since they just opened recently.  I can't speak on the authenticity of the dishes, but they taste great and I appreciate the level of spice indicated on the menu for each dish.
